SIMPLE: resolve
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Resolve
<hw>Re*solve"</hw> <pr>(r?*z?lv")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Resolved</conjf>
<pr>(-z?lvd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Resolving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>resolvere</ets>,
<ets>resolutum</ets>, to untie, loosen, relax, enfeeble; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>solvere</ets> to loosen, dissolve: cf. F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧soudare</ets> to resolve. See <er>Solve</er>, and cf.
<er>Resolve</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, <er>Resolute</er>,
<er>Resolution</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate the component
parts of; to reduce to the constituent elements; -- said of compound
substances; hence, sometimes, to melt, or dissolve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, that this too too solid flesh would melt,⟦br⟧
Thaw, and <qex>resolve</qex> itself into a dew!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye immortal souls, who once were men,⟦br⟧
And now <qex>resolved</qex> to elements again.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reduce to simple or intelligible notions; -- said
of complex ideas or obscure questions; to make clear or certain; to free
from doubt; to disentangle; to unravel; to explain; hence, to clear up,
or dispel, as doubt; <as>as, to <ex>resolve</ex> a riddle</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Resolve</xex> my doubt.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the <qex>resolving</qex> whereof we must first know that the
Jews were commanded to divorce an unbelieving Gentile.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to perceive or understand; to acquaint; to
inform; to convince; to assure; to make certain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sir, be <qex>resolved</qex>. I must and will come.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Resolve</qex> me, Reason, which of these is worse,⟦br⟧
Want with a full, or with an empty purse?</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In health, good air, pleasure, riches, I am <qex>resolved</qex> it
can not be equaled by any region.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We must be <qex>resolved</qex> how the law can be pure and
perspicuous, and yet throw a polluted skirt over these Eleusinian
mysteries.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To determine or decide in purpose; to make ready in
mind; to fix; to settle; <as>as, he was <ex>resolved</ex> by an
unexpected event</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To express, as an opinion or determination, by
resolution and vote; to declare or decide by a formal vote; -- followed
by a clause; <as>as, the house resolved (or, it was resolved by the
house) that no money should be apropriated (or, to appropriate no
money)</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To change or convert by resolution or formal vote;
-- used only reflexively; <as>as, the house <ex>resolved</ex> itself
into a committee of the whole</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To solve, as a problem, by
enumerating the several things to be done, in order to obtain what is
required; to find the answer to, or the result of.</def>
<rj><au>Hutton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To dispere or scatter; to discuss,
as an inflammation or a tumor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To let the tones (as of a discord)
follow their several tendencies, resulting in a concord.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To relax; to lay at ease.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To resolve a nebula</b></col>.<fld>(Astron.)</fld>
<cd>See <cref>Resolution of a nebula</cref>, under
<er>Resolution</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To solve; analyze; unravel;
disentangle.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resolve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Resolve
<hw>Re*solve"</hw> <pr>(r?-z?lv")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[The sense
⟦ldquo⟧to be convinced, to determine⟦rdquo⟧ comes from the idea of
loosening, breaking up into parts, analyzing, hence,
determining.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be separated into its component parts or distinct
principles; to undergo resolution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To melt; to dissolve; to become fluid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the blood stagnates in any part, it first coagulates, then
<qex>resolves</qex>, and turns alkaline.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthhnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be settled in opinion; to be convinced.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let men <qex>resolve</qex> of that as they plaease.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To form a purpose; to make a decision; especially,
to determine after reflection; <as>as, to <ex>resolve</ex> on a better
course of life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To determine; decide; conclude;
purpose.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resolve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Resolve
<hw>Re*solve"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of resolving
or making clear; resolution; solution.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To give a full
<xex>resolve</xex> of that which is so much controverted.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which has been resolved on or determined;
decisive conclusion; fixed purpose; determination; also, legal or
official determination; a legislative declaration; a
resolution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor is your firm <qex>resolve</qex> unknown.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Caesar's approach has summoned us together,⟦br⟧
And Rome attends her fate from our <qex>resolves</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resolved</ent>⟦br⟧
